HEADWORD: Kinesodic
<hw>Kin`e*sod"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/ motion +
<?/ way: cf. F. <ets>kin⟦eacute⟧sodigue</ets>.]</ety>
<fld>(Physiol.)</fld> <def>Conveying motion; <as>as, <ex>kinesodic</ex>
substance</as>; -- applied esp. to the spinal cord, because it is
capable of conveying doth voluntary and reflex motor impulses, without
itself being affected by motor impulses applied to it
directly.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>kinetic</ent>⟦br⟧
